site_notes: Kinney Shores is part of Saco and is a popular tourist and resident beach. The closest road to the start of the 100m site is Shore Ave for a landmark. Residents that I spoke with said that they regularly clean the beach themselves. Trashcans were located on every boardwalk but were off of the beach because high tide water marks go right up to the dunes. Signs located on the street at the beginning of the boardwalk state fireworks are prohibited, dogs to be leashed April 1st - September 30th, a marine mammal hotline number for reporting, and no further rules were posted. Part of the 100m site is an endangered Piping Plover nesting area and part of the dunes are roped off for protection. They are monitored by the Maine Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife and also by Saco volunteers. Goosefare Brook runs right alongside this site and empties into Saco Bay in the Gulf of Maine. This is an intertidal creek and in this area strong currents are present, changing sandbars, and constant shifting of the sand.

survey_photos: Debris from Transect 40 .jpg,Trash Can with Other Ppl Picking up Rope and Debris .jpg,Debris From Rest of 100m.jpg,Debris from Transect 85 .jpg,Debris from Transect 65.jpg,Begining of 100m Looking Down to Ocean.jpg,Looking Toward Dunes at End of 100m.jpg,Looking Inward at Begining of 100m .jpg,Looking Inward at End of 100m .jpg
survey_notes: There were 13 debris items smaller than 2.5 cm collected. Municipal beach cleaning with vehicle rakers had been done in the morning. Low tide was at 7:16am and conducted survey at 9:00am. The high water mark from previous high tide was close to the dunes. Looking into trash cans on the beach we could see that other people had been cleaning and throwing away debris like pieces of rope. Which could help explain why we didn't find any marine debris in transect 15.
reason_site_selection: "I like this beach,popular tourist/recreation area,it is relatively clean"
site_photos: Temple Ave.jpg,More Plovers.jpg,Plovers.jpg,Trash B.jpg,Trash D.jpg,Trash C.jpg,Weymouth Beach.jpg,Weymouth Beach Full View .jpg,Temple Beach View .jpg,Beach Signs .jpg,Full Beach View To Ocean.jpg,Trash A.jpg
site_notes: Ocean Park is part of Old Orchard Beach and is a popular tourist beach. A beach cleaning vehicle is used for raking the sand, started on 05/19/2023, ends after Labor Day, and is cleaned in the mornings. Part of the 100 meter area is an endangered piping plover nesting area and the dunes are roped off and monitored by Maine Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife. Trashcans are located on the beach at every boardwalk with signs stating carry out all trash, no smoking on beach, no public drinking, fireworks are prohibited, and hours when dogs are allowed. This beach is located within Saco Bay, which is a part of the Gulf of Maine. Goosefare Brook is 0.24 km from the survey site and this tidal creek empties into Saco Bay.

transect_notes: Part of a broken metal lobster trap recorded under other metal as wire. This also shows the smaller pieces of debris that we have been finding are coming from the coating to the wire traps.
survey_notes: Trashcan is usually present at this boardwalk on Porter Rd but had been removed for unknown reasons. Contacted the town to have it brought back because debris was scattered in this area. Along the dunes at the start of the 100m transect and the creek is the Rachel Carson National Wildlife Refuge. Total of 116 pieces of debris smaller than 2.5cm were found. Beach cleaning was done by the town in the morning but does not appear that their vehicle rakers go as far as Porter Rd boardwalk.

site_notes: Ocean Park is part of Old Orchard Beach and is a popular tourist beach. A beach cleaning vehicle is used for raking the sand, started on 05/19/2023, ends after Labor Day, and is cleaned in the mornings. Trashcans are located on the beach at every boardwalk with signs stating carry out all trash, no smoking on beach, no public drinking, fireworks are prohibited, and hours when dogs are allowed. This beach is located within Saco Bay, which is a part of the Gulf of Maine. Goosefare Brook is right along side this survey site and is a tidal creek that empties into Saco Bay. There are strong currents coming in and out with the tides in this area, which causes constant sand movement, growing sand areas, and erosion.

transect_notes: Trashcan is present at this close boardwalk at New Salt Rd. Noticed that the farther away from the mouth of the creek, the less amount of debris was found.
